1111
00:46:12,630 --> 00:46:23,530
The calculation suggests that Peter is closer in height than he actually is.

1112
00:46:26,940 --> 00:46:27,400
Here.

1113
00:46:27,480 --> 00:46:34,300
The numbers do not match what we observe in reality.

1114
00:46:34,300 --> 00:46:41,000
As a result, the mapping fails the validity test.

1115
00:46:41,000 --> 00:46:48,000
This comparison highlights an important point.

1116
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:51,000
Validity is not about having numbers.

1117
00:46:51,000 --> 00:47:05,780
It is about whether those numbers correctly reflect real relationships.

1118
00:47:05,780 --> 00:47:37,260
If a metric changes the meaning of what we observe, it cannot be trusted.

1119
00:47:40,239 --> 00:47:45,239
In software measurement, the same logic applies.

1120
00:47:45,239 --> 00:47:46,239
It is valid.

1121
00:47:46,239 --> 00:47:54,440
If a metric suggests improvements while developers experience growing complexity,

1122
00:47:54,440 --> 00:47:57,900
the problem lies in the metric.

1123
00:47:57,900 --> 00:48:05,500
A valid measure always protects the original meaning of the observation.

