1148
00:50:54,070 --> 00:50:59,119
These methods do not replace formal measurements.

1149
00:50:59,619 --> 00:51:02,440
They act as a starting point.

1150
00:51:04,210 --> 00:51:11,489
By using subjective ratings, early empirical relations can be established.

1151
00:51:11,489 --> 00:51:22,559
Once these relations become stable and shared, more formal metrics can be developed.

1152
00:51:22,559 --> 00:51:29,989
In software engineering, this step is often necessary.

1153
00:51:32,769 --> 00:51:42,050
Complex qualities are first judged qualitatively before they can be measured quantitatively.

1154
00:51:43,460 --> 00:51:46,559
Subjective ratings, therefore, help bridge this.

1155
00:51:46,900 --> 00:51:51,420
The gap between intuition and formal measurements.

1156
00:52:03,969 --> 00:52:05,829
The software definition problem.

1157
00:52:05,829 --> 00:52:11,880
In physical sciences, units are clear and shared.

1158
00:52:13,860 --> 00:52:20,670
When we say one inch, everyone understands exactly what that means.

1159
00:52:22,079 --> 00:52:25,360
In software, the situation is very different.

1160
00:52:26,699 --> 00:52:29,179
When something that sounds simple,

1161
00:52:31,750 --> 00:52:37,300
one line of code depends on how it is defined.

1162
00:52:40,570 --> 00:52:42,829
Questions appear immediately.

1163
00:52:42,829 --> 00:52:46,809
Should executable code be counted?

1164
00:52:47,630 --> 00:52:49,690
What about declarations?

1165
00:52:50,429 --> 00:52:52,869
Do comments belong to the count?

1166
00:52:53,550 --> 00:52:57,409
Should blank lines be included or ignored?

1167
00:53:08,400 --> 00:53:12,940
Without clear answers, the same problem can produce different results.

1168
00:53:13,460 --> 00:53:22,309
Two teams may measure the same code and report different values.

1169
00:53:22,949 --> 00:53:25,409
This is not a problem of calculation.

1170
00:53:25,630 --> 00:53:27,670
This is a problem of definition.

1171
00:53:31,619 --> 00:53:37,420
A well-known attempt to solve this comes from David Wheeler.

1172
00:53:50,070 --> 00:53:56,780
He defines a line of code as a line that ends with a new line

1173
00:53:56,780 --> 00:53:58,099
and contains a new line.

1174
00:53:58,099 --> 00:53:58,119
This line contains a new line.

1175
00:53:58,119 --> 00:54:03,599
It contains at least one non-white space,

1176
00:54:03,980 --> 00:54:05,760
a non-comment character.

1177
00:54:06,440 --> 00:54:19,340
This definition may not be perfect, but it is precise.

1178
00:54:20,969 --> 00:54:26,010
Most importantly, it is explicit and repeatable.

1179
00:54:26,630 --> 00:54:28,530
The key lesson is simple.

1180
00:54:29,530 --> 00:54:35,849
A metric has no meaning unless the mapping rule is clearly stated.

1181
00:54:37,559 --> 00:54:43,059
If the rule is void, the numbers cannot be trusted.

1182
00:54:44,190 --> 00:54:49,690
Different interpretations will lead to different conclusions.

1183
00:54:49,690 --> 00:55:03,690
If the software matrix clearly comes before measurement,

1184
00:55:05,219 --> 00:55:07,539
only after definitions are fixed,

1185
00:55:07,539 --> 00:55:12,760
and only after definitions,

1186
00:55:13,480 --> 00:55:16,960
