reflects the real priorities.

1223
00:59:24,400 --> 00:59:30,400
Yes, measurement begins with understanding,

1224
00:59:30,400 --> 00:59:33,849
not calculation.

1225
00:59:33,849 --> 01:00:01,550
The mapping, yes.

1226
01:00:01,550 --> 01:00:06,860
After defining the order of importance,

1227
01:00:06,860 --> 01:00:09,860
the next step is to assign numbers.

1228
01:00:09,860 --> 01:00:12,260
The goal here is not precise.

1229
01:00:12,260 --> 01:00:15,260
Not precision, but consistency.

1230
01:00:15,260 --> 01:00:19,519
The numbers must represent the hierarchy

1231
01:00:19,519 --> 01:00:22,519
that was already agreed on.

1232
01:00:22,519 --> 01:00:29,320
Data loss was identified as the most critical value.

1233
01:00:29,320 --> 01:00:32,510
Incorrect output comes next,

1234
01:00:32,510 --> 01:00:36,510
but followed by delay.

1235
01:00:36,510 --> 01:00:44,739
One possible mapping assigns a high value

1236
01:00:44,739 --> 01:00:45,739
to a data loss.

1237
01:00:45,739 --> 01:00:50,739
And lower values to the others.

1238
01:00:50,739 --> 01:00:56,969
In this case, 69 is assigned to data loss,

1239
01:00:56,969 --> 01:01:01,289
4 to incorrect output,

1240
01:01:01,289 --> 01:01:05,019
and 3 to delay.

1241
01:01:05,019 --> 01:01:18,710
These numbers are preserved the original order.

1242
01:01:18,710 --> 01:01:22,710
The most severe problem still has the largest value.

1243
01:01:22,710 --> 01:01:26,320
Because the hierarchy remains intact,

1244
01:01:26,320 --> 01:01:27,320
but this is not the case.

1245
01:01:27,320 --> 01:01:30,320
But this mapping is valid.

1246
01:01:30,320 --> 01:01:34,320
Now consider a different assignment.

1247
01:01:34,320 --> 01:01:39,320
Data loss and incorrect output keep the same values.

1248
01:01:39,320 --> 01:01:57,460
But delay is assigned to higher number.

1249
01:01:57,460 --> 01:02:00,460
This creates a problem.

1250
01:02:00,460 --> 01:02:05,460
The numbers now suggest that delay is worse

1251
01:02:05,460 --> 01:02:07,460
than incorrect output.

1252
01:02:07,460 --> 01:02:10,460
That conclusion directly conflicts

1253
01:02:10,460 --> 01:02:13,460
with the earlier observation.

1254
01:02:13,460 --> 01:02:18,820
As a result, the mapping becomes invalid.

1255
01:02:18,820 --> 01:02:24,260
This issue is not the size of the numbers.

1256
01:02:24,260 --> 01:02:28,260
It is meaning they create.

1257
01:02:28,260 --> 01:02:34,380
A metric must never change priorities

1258
01:02:34,380 --> 01:02:38,380
that were defined in the empirical world.

1259
01:02:38,380 --> 01:02:43,039
If it does,

1260
01:02:43,039 --> 01:02:52,579
the metric no longer reflects reality.

1261
01:02:52,579 --> 01:02:59,690
This step shows why mapping is not arbitrary.

1262
01:02:59,690 --> 01:03:02,690
Numbers must be chosen carefully

1263
01:03:02,690 --> 01:03:06,690
so that they protect the original understanding

1264
01:03:06,690 --> 01:03:08,690
of severity.

1265
01:03:08,690 --> 01:03:12,099
Only then can the metrics

1266
01:03:12,099 --> 01:03:18,809
be trusted in decision making.

1267
01:03:18,809 --> 01:03:39,199
Measurement is not the final goal.

1268
01:03:39,199 --> 01:03:43,320
It is part of a larger process

1269
01:03:43,320 --> 01:03:46,320
that connects reality to decision making.

1270
01:03:46,320 --> 01:03:51,469
Everything starts in the real world.

1271
01:03:51,469 --> 01:03:55,469
We observe entities and their attributes,

1272
01:03:55,469 --> 01:03:57,469
such as systems,

1273
01:03:57,469 --> 01:03:59,630
components,

1274
01:03:59,630 --> 01:04:00,630
failures,

1275
01:04:00,630 --> 01:04:02,630
or processes.

1276
01:04:02,630 --> 01:04:05,980
Measurement acts as a bridge.

1277
01:04:05,980 --> 01:04:09,019
It provides rules that map

1278
01:04:09,019 --> 01:04:11,019
these real-world observations

1279
01:04:11,019 --> 01:04:14,019
into numbers or symbols.

1280
01:04:14,019 --> 01:04:34,789
Okay.

1281
01:04:34,789 --> 01:04:43,579
Once the mapping is applied,

1282
01:04:43,579 --> 01:04:47,000
data is created.

1283
01:04:47,000 --> 01:04:48,000
At this stage,

1284
01:04:48,000 --> 01:04:52,000
we no longer deal directly with reality,

1285
01:04:52,000 --> 01:04:55,000
but with its representation.

1286
01:04:55,000 --> 01:04:59,000
Data by itself is still not enough.

1287
01:04:59,000 --> 01:05:03,000
Numbers only become useful

1288
01:05:03,000 --> 01:05:09,059
when they are organized and interpreted.

1289
01:05:09,059 --> 01:05:18,019
This is where models come into play.

1290
01:05:18,019 --> 01:05:20,019
Models combine data

1291
01:05:20,019 --> 01:05:24,019
to focus on specific concerns,

1292
01:05:24,019 --> 01:05:29,059
such as cost, quality, or maturity.

1293
01:05:30,059 --> 01:05:35,280
A model does not try to capture everything.

1294
01:05:35,280 --> 01:05:38,340
It removes details in order

1295
01:05:38,340 --> 01:05:41,340
to highlight what matters

1296
01:05:41,340 --> 01:05:43,340
for a given purpose.

1297
01:05:43,340 --> 01:05:45,340
Because of this,

1298
01:05:45,340 --> 01:05:47,340
every model reflects

1299
01:05:47,340 --> 01:05:51,559
a particular point of view.

1300
01:05:51,559 --> 01:05:55,559
The same data can support different models,

1301
01:05:55,559 --> 01:06:00,199
depending on the question being asked.

1302
01:06:00,199 --> 01:06:04,420
The final step is decision-making.

1303
01:06:04,420 --> 01:06:10,789
Models support control,

1304
01:06:10,789 --> 01:06:13,789
comparison, and improvement.

1305
01:06:13,789 --> 01:06:18,789
If measurements are weak,

1306
01:06:18,789 --> 01:06:22,789
models become unreliable.

1307
01:06:22,789 --> 01:06:27,050
And if models are unreliable,

1308
01:06:27,050 --> 01:06:31,050
decisions are based on false confidence.

1309
01:06:31,050 --> 01:06:38,780
This is why careful measurement is essential.

1310
01:06:38,780 --> 01:06:49,090
It determines the quality of everything that follows.

1311
01:06:49,090 --> 01:06:53,980
Good decisions do not start with models.

1312
01:06:53,980 --> 01:07:02,699
They start with sound measurements.

1313
01:07:02,699 --> 01:07:31,860
The danger of context.

1314
01:07:31,860 --> 01:07:33,860
A single metric can tell

1315
01:07:33,860 --> 01:07:36,019
very different stories,

1316
01:07:36,019 --> 01:07:39,019
depending on how it is used.

1317
01:07:39,019 --> 01:07:45,829
False per clock

1318
01:07:45,829 --> 01:07:57,409
is a common example.

1319
01:07:57,409 --> 01:07:58,409
Yes.

1320
01:07:58,409 --> 01:08:00,750
On its own,

1321
01:08:00,750 --> 01:08:03,750
the number looks clear and objective.

1322
01:08:03,750 --> 01:08:05,750
However, its meaning

1323
01:08:05,750 --> 01:08:08,750
strongly depends on context.

1324
01:08:08,750 --> 01:08:11,230
When we focus

1325
01:08:11,230 --> 01:08:14,230
on the testing process,

1326
01:08:14,230 --> 01:08:17,229
this metric can be useful.

1327
01:08:17,229 --> 01:08:21,859
A higher number may indicate

1328
01:08:21,859 --> 01:08:25,859
that testing is effective.

1329
01:08:25,859 --> 01:08:28,859
More defects are being discovered,

1330
01:08:28,859 --> 01:08:30,859
not hidden.

1331
01:08:30,859 --> 01:08:33,380
Problems appear

1332
01:08:33,380 --> 01:08:35,380
when the same metric is used

1333
01:08:35,380 --> 01:08:37,380
to judge programmers.

1334
01:08:37,380 --> 01:08:41,109
False per clock ignores

1335
01:08:41,109 --> 01:08:45,109
code difficulty and complexity.

1336
01:08:45,109 --> 01:08:55,500
Writing simple code

1337
01:08:55,500 --> 01:08:58,500
and writing safety-critical code

1338
01:08:58,500 --> 01:09:01,199
are treated the same.

1339
01:09:01,199 --> 01:09:03,199
In this context,

1340
01:09:03,199 --> 01:09:06,420
the metric becomes misleading.

1341
01:09:06,420 --> 01:09:09,420
It punishes complexity

1342
01:09:09,420 --> 01:09:13,420
instead of measuring scale.

1343
01:09:13,420 --> 01:09:15,420
Using the metric

1344
01:09:15,420 --> 01:09:18,420
to evaluate code quality

1345
01:09:18,420 --> 01:09:23,020
is even more risky,

1346
01:09:23,020 --> 01:09:26,020
as high fault rates

1347
01:09:26,020 --> 01:09:29,020
may mean poor quality.

1348
01:09:29,020 --> 01:09:31,340
But it may also mean

1349
01:09:31,340 --> 01:09:34,340
very true testing.

1350
01:09:34,340 --> 01:09:40,050
The number alone

1351
01:09:40,050 --> 01:09:43,050
cannot separate these explanations.

1352
01:09:43,050 --> 01:09:47,050
This is the code danger of context.

1353
01:09:47,050 --> 01:09:49,460
Metrics do not carry meaning

1354
01:09:49,460 --> 01:09:51,460
by themselves.

1355
01:09:51,460 --> 01:09:53,460
Meaning comes from

1356
01:09:53,460 --> 01:09:56,460
how and why they are applied.

1357
01:09:56,460 --> 01:10:06,590
When context is ignored,

1358
01:10:06,590 --> 01:10:09,590
metrics create false conclusions.

1359
01:10:09,590 --> 01:10:14,590
Decisions based on those conclusions

1360
01:10:14,590 --> 01:10:16,590
can easily be wrong.

1361
01:10:16,590 --> 01:10:19,420
Good measurement always starts

1362
01:10:19,420 --> 01:10:21,420
with a clear question.

1363
01:10:21,420 --> 01:10:23,520
Only then

1364
01:10:23,520 --> 01:10:26,520
can the metric

1365
01:10:26,520 --> 01:10:31,340
be interpreted correctly.

1366
01:10:31,340 --> 01:10:33,340
Without context,

1367
01:10:33,340 --> 01:10:35,340
even well-designed metrics

1368
01:10:35,340 --> 01:10:38,699
become dangerous.

1369
01:10:38,699 --> 01:10:41,529
And this is the last

1370
01:10:41,529 --> 01:10:43,579
not last,

1371
01:10:43,579 --> 01:10:46,579
we have only two slides here.

1372
01:10:46,579 --> 01:10:48,579
Slide number 14.

1373
01:10:48,579 --> 01:10:50,380
Okay.

1374
01:10:50,380 --> 01:10:52,899
When its metrics

1375
01:10:52,899 --> 01:10:55,899
do not appear by accident,

1376
01:10:55,899 --> 01:10:58,279
they follow a clear

1377
01:10:58,279 --> 01:11:00,279
and disciplined process.

1378
01:11:00,279 --> 01:11:02,470
The first step is

1379
01:11:02,470 --> 01:11:05,470
to identify the attributes.

1380
01:11:05,470 --> 01:11:09,500
Means being very specific about

1381
01:11:09,500 --> 01:11:12,500
what is being studied.

1382
01:11:12,500 --> 01:11:16,329
Would you go

1383
01:11:16,329 --> 01:11:19,329
to go to measurements?

1384
01:11:19,329 --> 01:11:22,260
The next step focuses

1385
01:11:22,260 --> 01:11:24,260
on observation.

1386
01:11:24,260 --> 01:11:26,260
What relationships can be seen

1387
01:11:26,260 --> 01:11:28,260
in the real world?

1388
01:11:28,260 --> 01:11:29,260
For example,

1389
01:11:29,260 --> 01:11:31,260
one system may respond

1390
01:11:31,260 --> 01:11:34,289
faster than another.

1391
01:11:34,289 --> 01:11:37,420
These observations from

1392
01:11:37,420 --> 01:11:41,510
form empirical relations.

1393
01:11:41,510 --> 01:11:43,510
They exist before any numbers

1394
01:11:43,510 --> 01:11:45,510
are introduced.

1395
01:11:45,510 --> 01:11:46,510
After that,

1396
01:11:46,510 --> 01:11:49,510
rules for assigning numbers

1397
01:11:49,510 --> 01:11:50,510
must be defined.

1398
01:11:50,510 --> 01:11:52,510
This includes decisions

1399
01:11:52,510 --> 01:11:54,510
such as counting methods

1400
01:11:54,510 --> 01:11:56,510
and thresholds.

1401
01:11:56,510 --> 01:11:58,640
At this stage,

1402
01:11:58,640 --> 01:12:00,640
consistency matters

1403
01:12:00,640 --> 01:12:02,640
more than precision.

1404
01:12:02,640 --> 01:12:06,340
Once numbers are assigned,

1405
01:12:06,340 --> 01:12:09,340
a critical check is required.

1406
01:12:09,340 --> 01:12:11,340
The representation condition

1407
01:12:11,340 --> 01:12:13,340
must be tested.

1408
01:12:13,340 --> 01:12:15,500
The key question is

1409
01:12:15,500 --> 01:12:16,500
simple.

1410
01:12:16,500 --> 01:12:18,500
Do the numbers

1411
01:12:18,500 --> 01:12:19,500
still reflect

1412
01:12:19,500 --> 01:12:21,500
the original observations?

1413
01:12:21,500 --> 01:12:23,500
If the answer is no,

1414
01:12:23,500 --> 01:12:26,500
the metric is invalid.

1415
01:12:26,500 --> 01:12:29,500
Even well-calculated numbers

1416
01:12:29,500 --> 01:12:31,500
must be rejected

1417
01:12:31,500 --> 01:12:33,500
if they change meaning.

1418
01:12:33,500 --> 01:12:36,180
An important trade-off

1419
01:12:36,180 --> 01:12:38,180
appears here.

1420
01:12:38,180 --> 01:12:40,180
As empirical relations

1421
01:12:40,180 --> 01:12:42,180
become richer,

1422
01:12:42,180 --> 01:12:44,180
fewer valid measures

1423
01:12:44,180 --> 01:12:46,180
are possible.

1424
01:12:46,180 --> 01:12:47,689
However,

1425
01:12:47,689 --> 01:12:49,689
the remaining measures

1426
01:12:49,689 --> 01:12:52,689
carry much stronger meaning.

1427
01:12:52,689 --> 01:12:57,319
This protocol encourages

1428
01:12:57,319 --> 01:12:59,319
careful thinking.

1429
01:12:59,319 --> 01:13:02,319
It limits measurements' freedom

1430
01:13:02,319 --> 01:13:05,319
in order to predict correctness.

1431
01:13:05,319 --> 01:13:08,579
Valid metrics are not chosen

1432
01:13:08,579 --> 01:13:10,579
because they are easy.

1433
01:13:10,579 --> 01:13:12,579
They are chosen because

1434
01:13:12,579 --> 01:13:15,579
they respect reality.

1435
01:13:15,579 --> 01:13:24,859
Yes.

1436
01:13:24,859 --> 01:13:28,390
The foundation

1437
01:13:28,390 --> 01:13:30,390
of insights

1438
01:13:30,390 --> 01:13:31,390
measurements

1439
01:13:31,390 --> 01:13:32,390
is often used

1440
01:13:32,390 --> 01:13:33,390
as a tool

1441
01:13:33,390 --> 01:13:35,390
for discovery.

1442
01:13:35,390 --> 01:13:36,520
We measure

1443
01:13:36,520 --> 01:13:37,520
because we want

1444
01:13:37,520 --> 01:13:39,520
to learn something new.

1445
01:13:39,520 --> 01:13:40,970
However,

1446
01:13:40,970 --> 01:13:42,970
representational theory

1447
01:13:42,970 --> 01:13:46,159
highlights an important paradox.

1448
01:13:46,159 --> 01:13:47,159
True measurement

1449
01:13:47,159 --> 01:13:49,159
does not come

1450
01:13:49,159 --> 01:13:52,579
before understanding.

1451
01:13:52,579 --> 01:13:54,579
If we do not understand

1452
01:13:54,579 --> 01:13:58,579
and attribute intuitively,

1453
01:13:58,579 --> 01:14:00,579
numbers will not help.

1454
01:14:00,579 --> 01:14:02,859
They may look precise,

1455
01:14:02,859 --> 01:14:05,859
but they can still be misleading.

1456
01:14:05,859 --> 01:14:08,470
Insights always start

1457
01:14:08,470 --> 01:14:11,470
before calculation.

1458
01:14:11,470 --> 01:14:12,470
First,

1459
01:14:12,470 --> 01:14:13,470
there must be

1460
01:14:13,470 --> 01:14:15,470
a clear mental picture

1461
01:14:15,470 --> 01:14:17,470
of what is being observed.

1462
01:14:17,470 --> 01:14:19,789
This intuition helps us

1463
01:14:19,789 --> 01:14:21,789
to define meaningful relations.

1464
01:14:21,789 --> 01:14:23,789
Only after that

1465
01:14:23,789 --> 01:14:26,789
can measurement make sense.

1466
01:14:26,789 --> 01:14:30,329
Skipping this step

1467
01:14:30,329 --> 01:14:33,329
leads to weak metrics.

1468
01:14:33,329 --> 01:14:34,329
In such cases,

1469
01:14:34,329 --> 01:14:37,329
numbers hide confusion

1470
01:14:37,329 --> 01:14:40,329
instead of revealing truth.

1471
01:14:40,329 --> 01:14:42,329
The correct order

1472
01:14:42,329 --> 01:14:44,329
is simple but strict.

1473
01:14:44,329 --> 01:14:46,710
Refine intuition first,

1474
01:14:46,710 --> 01:14:48,710
then define relations.

1475
01:14:48,710 --> 01:14:50,710
Only then

1476
01:14:50,710 --> 01:14:51,710
does measurement

1477
01:14:51,710 --> 01:14:53,710
become valuable.

1478
01:14:53,710 --> 01:14:54,710
Strong insight

1479
01:14:54,710 --> 01:14:56,710
creates strong metrics.

1480
01:14:56,710 --> 01:14:58,710
Without insight,

1481
01:14:58,710 --> 01:14:59,710
measurement is just

1482
01:14:59,710 --> 01:15:00,710
what?

1483
01:15:00,710 --> 01:15:01,739
Counting.

1484
